(43, 8, 1, 41, 13, 3, 3, 'mount of Olives', 'Connection through Mount of Olives', 'Both passages emphasize the mount of Olives as a significant location for Jesus. In John, Jesus goes to the mount, while in Mark, he teaches there, indicating its importance in his ministry.', 'theme', 0.293, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 2, 40, 26, 55, 55, NULL, 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' role as a teacher in the temple. In John 8:2, he is teaching the people, while in Matthew 26:55, he recalls teaching daily in the temple before his arrest.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 2, 42, 4, 20, 20, 'sat down, and taught them', 'Teaching and Authority in Context', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching in a seated position, indicating authority. In John, he teaches in the temple, while in Luke, he teaches in the synagogue, capturing the attention of the people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 2, 42, 21, 37, 37, NULL, 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' teaching in the temple. John 8:2 highlights his teaching in the morning, while Luke 21:37 notes his daytime teaching there.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 2, 40, 5, 1, 2, 'taught them', 'Teaching in Different Settings', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching the people, with John 8:2 highlighting his presence in the temple and Matthew 5:1-2 describing him teaching on a mountain. This connection highlights the continuity of Jesus'' role as a teacher in various locations.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 2, 21, 9, 10, 10, NULL, 'Work and Teaching Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of active engagement in both teaching and work. In John 8:2, Jesus teaches the people, while Ecclesiastes 9:10 emphasizes doing work with might.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 2, 24, 25, 3, 3, 'early in the morning', 'Teaching and Early Rising', 'This connection highlights the theme of early rising and teaching. Both passages emphasize the act of rising early to communicate important messages, whether it is Jesus teaching in the temple or Jeremiah delivering the word of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 2, 24, 44, 4, 4, 'early in the morning', 'Early Teaching and Warnings', 'This connection highlights the theme of early action in both passages. In John, Jesus teaches early in the morning, while in Jeremiah, God sends prophets early to warn against wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 5, 3, 20, 10, 10, 'Moses in the law commanded us', 'Connection of Adultery Punishment', 'This connection highlights the legal consequence of adultery in both passages. John 8:5 references the law of Moses, which includes the death penalty for adulterers as stated in Leviticus 20:10.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 5, 5, 22, 21, 24, 'that such should be stoned', 'Connection of Stoning Commandments', 'Both passages emphasize the punishment of stoning for adultery and sexual immorality. John 8:5 references the law of Moses, which is detailed in Deuteronomy 22:21-24, highlighting the consequences for such actions.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 5, 26, 16, 38, 40, 'stoned', 'Judgment and Stoning Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and stoning present in both passages. In John 8:5, the act of stoning is referenced in relation to the law, while Ezekiel 16:40 describes a judgment involving stoning as a consequence of unfaithfulness.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 5, 40, 5, 17, 17, 'the law', 'Law and Fulfillment Connection', 'This connection highlights the relationship between the law given by Moses and Jesus'' purpose. Both passages emphasize the significance of the law, with John referencing the command to stone and Matthew affirming Jesus'' role in fulfilling the law.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 5, 40, 19, 6, 8, 'Moses in the law commanded us', 'Divorce and Mosaic Law', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Moses in relation to divorce. The SOURCE verse references Moses'' command, while the TARGET passage discusses Moses'' allowance for divorce due to human hardness of heart.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 5, 26, 23, 47, 47, 'stoned', 'Connection of Punishment and Law', 'This connection highlights the theme of punishment prescribed by the law. Both passages address the act of stoning as a form of judgment against wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 6, 24, 17, 13, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Writing in Earth', 'This connection highlights the act of writing in the earth, as seen in both passages. In John 8:6, Jesus writes on the ground, while Jeremiah 17:13 mentions those forsaking the Lord being ''written in the earth.''', 'keyword', 0.517, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 6, 42, 10, 25, 25, 'tempting him', 'Testing Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals attempting to test Jesus'' wisdom and authority. In both passages, the characters approach Jesus with the intent to challenge or tempt him, revealing a common narrative thread of scrutiny.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 6, 19, 38, 12, 14, 'as though he heard them not', 'Silence in the Face of Accusation', 'This connection highlights the theme of silence in response to accusations. Both passages depict a figure who chooses not to engage with those seeking to harm or accuse them, emphasizing a deliberate act of ignoring malicious intent.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 6, 21, 3, 7, 7, 'as though he heard them not', 'Silence and Speaking in Context', 'This connection highlights the theme of timing in communication. In John 8:6, Jesus chooses to remain silent initially, paralleling Ecclesiastes 3:7''s notion of a ''time to keep silence.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 6, 30, 5, 10, 10, NULL, 'Rejection of Righteousness Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by those who speak truthfully. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the disdain for those who challenge wrongdoing or speak uprightly.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 6, 40, 19, 3, 3, 'tempting him', 'Temptation of Jesus by Pharisees', 'Both passages emphasize the Pharisees'' attempts to tempt Jesus. In John 8:6, they seek to accuse him, while in Matthew 19:3, they question him on divorce to trap him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 6, 4, 14, 22, 22, 'tempting him', 'Temptation and Divine Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of temptation in both passages. In John 8:6, the Pharisees tempt Jesus, while in Numbers 14:22, God speaks of the Israelites tempting Him multiple times.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 7, 40, 7, 1, 5, 'He that is without sin among you', 'Judgment and Hypocrisy', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and self-examination. Both passages emphasize the need to consider one''s own faults before judging others.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 7, 45, 2, 21, 25, 'He that is without sin among you', 'Sin and Judgment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy in both passages. John 8:7 emphasizes the need for self-examination before judging others, while Romans 2:21-25 addresses the inconsistency of teaching moral laws while breaking them oneself.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 7, 45, 2, 1, 3, 'He that is without sin among you', 'Judgment and Sinfulness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of judgment and sinfulness. John 8:7 highlights the idea that those without sin should judge others, while Romans 2:1-3 warns against judging others when one is guilty of the same sins.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 7, 5, 17, 6, 7, 'let him first cast a stone', 'Connection of Witness and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of witnesses in judgment. John 8:7 highlights the need for sinlessness among those who judge, while Deuteronomy 17:6-7 specifies that witnesses must act first in executing judgment.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 7, 40, 23, 25, 28, 'He that is without sin among you', 'Hypocrisy and Inner Purity', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of inner purity over outward appearances. John 8:7''s call for self-examination resonates with Matthew 23:25-28''s critique of hypocrisy among the Pharisees.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 7, 51, 4, 6, 6, 'He that is without sin among you', 'Grace in Judgment and Speech', 'This connection highlights the importance of grace in both judgment and communication. John 8:7 emphasizes the need for self-reflection before casting judgment, while Colossians 4:6 encourages speech that is gracious and considerate.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 7, 58, 4, 12, 13, 'He that is without sin among you', 'Judgment and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and accountability in both passages. John 8:7 emphasizes the need for self-reflection before casting judgment, while Hebrews 4:12-13 speaks to the discernment of thoughts and intentions, revealing that all are accountable before God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 9, 21, 7, 22, 22, 'convicted by their own conscience', 'Conscience and Self-Reflection', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-awareness and conviction in both passages. In John 8:9, the individuals leave after being ''convicted by their own conscience,'' while Ecclesiastes 7:22 emphasizes that one''s heart knows their own faults, suggesting a shared focus on personal accountability.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 9, 45, 2, 15, 15, 'convicted by their own conscience', 'Conscience and Conviction Connection', 'This connection highlights the role of conscience in both passages. In John 8:9, the individuals are convicted by their own conscience, while Romans 2:15 discusses how conscience bears witness to the law written in their hearts.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 9, 62, 3, 20, 20, 'convicted by their own conscience', 'Conscience and Heart Condemnation', 'This connection highlights the theme of internal conviction, as both passages address the role of conscience and heart in judgment. In John 8:9, those present are ''convicted by their own conscience,'' while 1 John 3:20 speaks of the heart condemning us.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 9, 1, 42, 21, 22, 'convicted by their own conscience', 'Guilt and Conscience', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of guilt and the resulting conviction of conscience. In John, the accusers leave one by one, indicating their awareness of their own wrongdoing, while in Genesis, the brothers acknowledge their guilt regarding Joseph''s suffering.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 9, 18, 5, 12, 13, 'being convicted by their own conscience', 'Conviction and Craftiness', 'This connection highlights the theme of being convicted by one''s own conscience, as seen in John 8:9, which parallels Job 5:12-13''s idea of the wise being taken in their own craftiness. Both passages emphasize the consequences of one''s actions and intentions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 9, 19, 71, 13, 13, 'being convicted by their own conscience', 'Conviction and Adversaries', 'This connection highlights the theme of being confronted by one''s own conscience and the adversaries that seek to harm. Both passages reflect a struggle against those who oppose or seek to condemn, emphasizing the internal conflict and external reproach faced by individuals.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 9, 43, 8, 10, 10, NULL, 'Jesus and the Accuser''s Absence', 'This connection highlights the transition from the crowd''s departure to the woman''s encounter with Jesus. The absence of her accusers sets the stage for Jesus to address her directly, emphasizing her situation of being uncondemned.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 10, 23, 41, 11, 12, 'hath no man condemned thee', 'Shame and Accusation', 'This connection highlights the theme of shame and the absence of accusers. In both passages, the idea of those who contend or accuse being rendered as nothing is present.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 11, 43, 3, 17, 17, 'Neither do I condemn thee', 'Condemnation and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the absence of condemnation. Jesus'' statement in John 8:11 reflects his mission in John 3:17, where he clarifies that he was not sent to condemn but to save.', 'theme', 0.566, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
