(43, 8, 58, 43, 17, 5, 5, 'before Abraham was, I am', 'Eternal Existence of Jesus', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' existence before Abraham and before the world. Both passages emphasize His pre-existence and divine nature.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 58, 43, 1, 1, 2, 'I am', 'Connection of Divine Existence', 'This connection highlights the eternal nature of Jesus as both ''I am'' and ''the Word.'' Both passages emphasize the pre-existence of Jesus before Abraham and at the beginning of creation.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 58, 23, 44, 6, 6, 'I am', 'Divine Identity Connection', 'This connection highlights the assertion of divine identity in both passages. Jesus'' declaration of ''I am'' parallels the Lord''s self-identification as ''I am the first, and I am the last.''', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 58, 58, 13, 8, 8, 'I am', 'Eternal Nature of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the eternal existence of Jesus. In John 8:58, Jesus asserts His existence before Abraham, while Hebrews 13:8 emphasizes His unchanging nature through time.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 58, 66, 1, 8, 8, 'I am', 'Divine Identity and Eternity', 'This connection highlights the eternal nature of Jesus, as both passages affirm His existence before time and His role as the beginning and the ending. The phrase ''I am'' in John 8:58 parallels the declaration of ''I am Alpha and Omega'' in Revelation 1:8, emphasizing His divine identity.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 59, 43, 11, 8, 8, NULL, 'Threat of Stoning', 'This connection highlights the ongoing danger Jesus faced from the Jews, as both passages reference attempts to stone him. In John 8:59, the immediate threat is evident, while John 11:8 recalls this danger as the disciples express concern about returning to that location.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 59, 43, 10, 30, 33, 'took they up stones to cast at him', 'Reactions to Jesus'' Claims', 'Both passages emphasize the Jews'' violent reaction to Jesus'' claims about his identity. In each instance, they take up stones to stone him, indicating their rejection of his assertions. This connection highlights the escalating tension surrounding Jesus'' declarations of divinity.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 59, 3, 24, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Blasphemy and Punishment', 'Both passages emphasize the act of blasphemy and the severe consequences that follow. In John 8:59, the reaction of the crowd to Jesus suggests they viewed his words as blasphemous, aligning with the punishment outlined in Leviticus 24:16.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 8, 59, 42, 4, 29, 30, NULL, 'Jesus Passing Through Hostile Crowds', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' ability to navigate hostile situations unharmed. In each instance, he passes through a crowd intent on violence without being harmed.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
